{\b1 \cf21 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb400 
Synopsis
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Landlord brought unlawful detainer action against tenant, a former employee of landlord who was allowed to live in trailer house owned by landlord during his employment. The Superior Court, Franklin County, Fred R. Staples, J., entered judgment against tenant, and tenant appealed. The Court of Appeals, Munson, C. J., held that where tenant came upon premises with permission of landlord and where tenancy was terminable without notice and provided for no monthly or periodic payments, tenancy was what was denominated in common law as \u8220\'3ftenancy at will\u8221\'3f which was terminable only upon demand for possession, allowing tenant reasonable time to vacate, and unlawful detainer statute did not apply.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Judgment reversed and complaint dismissed.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
